  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The situation is like that in the Psalms of the time of Saul. The writer is a persecuted one, and in constant peril of his life. He has taken ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 86:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " out of the Elohimic ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 54:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and retained the Elohim as a proper name of God (cf. on the other hand ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 86:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 86:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); he has, however, altered זרים to זרים, which here, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 13:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (cf. however, ibid. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 25:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is the alternating word to עריצים. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 86:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " he supports his petition that follows by Jahve's testimony concerning Himself in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 34:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The appellation given to himself by the poet in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 86:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " recurs in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 116:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (cf. Wisd. 9:5). The poet calls himself \"the son of Thy handmaid\" as having been born into the relation to Him of servant; it is a relationship that has come to him by birth. How beautifully does the Adonaj come in here for the seventh time! He is even from his mother's womb the servant of the sovereign Lord, from whose omnipotence he can therefore also look for a miraculous interposition on his behalf. A \"token for good\" is a special dispensation, from which it becomes evident to him that God is kindly disposed towards him. לטובה as in the mouth of Nehemiah, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 5:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 13:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 8:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and also even in Jeremiah and earlier. ויבשׁוּ is just as parenthetical as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 26:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
